WEBVTT

00:19.227 --> 00:21.104
[in Spanish]
Do you get a lot of visitors?

00:21.938 --> 00:24.774
Because this is
the perfect place for entertaining.

00:25.066 --> 00:28.236
There's a wood-burning fire pit
in the courtyard, an outdoor bar,

00:28.319 --> 00:32.115
a second jacuzzi,
and a huge pool with a diving board.

00:34.451 --> 00:37.412
-Could we see what's over there?
-Yes, of course. Have a look.

00:41.750 --> 00:47.088
You won't find another property
with these amenities, acreage, or privacy,

00:47.172 --> 00:51.718
which seems so important
to many recent buyers.

00:51.968 --> 00:53.928
No one will bother you.

00:56.014 --> 00:57.766
I think you understand us.

00:59.059 --> 01:00.435
But there is one more thing.

01:01.603 --> 01:06.024
In our line of work, we often have
to do things that are not pleasant.

01:06.733 --> 01:08.276
But they're necessary.

01:08.943 --> 01:11.780
And we must be able to do them
without interference...

01:12.697 --> 01:14.157
or drawing too much attention.

01:15.950 --> 01:16.951
You understand me?

01:17.327 --> 01:18.411
[engine revs]

01:18.495 --> 01:19.579
[man screams]

01:20.163 --> 01:21.831
[man laughs]

01:24.959 --> 01:26.002
Stand over here.

01:28.338 --> 01:29.464
[grunts]

01:30.507 --> 01:31.508
[man laughing]

01:34.844 --> 01:35.678
[grunts]

01:35.762 --> 01:36.846
[gasps]

01:37.847 --> 01:40.058
Whoo! Whoo! Whoo!

01:41.810 --> 01:42.852
[Rafa laughing]

01:42.936 --> 01:43.895
[gasps]

01:50.693 --> 01:52.237
[Rafa]
Way to go, Chapo!

01:52.695 --> 01:53.738
I'll take it.

01:54.030 --> 01:55.198
Do you accept cash?

01:56.407 --> 01:57.283
Uh...

01:57.367 --> 01:59.786
[Rodrigo Amarante's "Tuyo" playing]

03:28.917 --> 03:30.585
[narrator in English]
So here's a few signs

03:30.668 --> 03:33.713
your town has become the center
of a major criminal operation.

03:33.796 --> 03:36.549
Suddenly, money's being spent all over.

03:36.633 --> 03:40.595
Cars, planes, real estate.
Everyone's buying.

03:41.638 --> 03:43.932
Want to avoid those long lines
at the bank?

03:44.682 --> 03:46.017
Buy the fucking place.

03:46.935 --> 03:48.311
Like any innovator,

03:48.394 --> 03:52.190
Miguel Ángel Félix Gallardo
saw things others didn't.

03:52.690 --> 03:56.361
And once his dream was realized,
it seemed so obvious,

03:56.444 --> 03:59.280
you couldn't believe
no one had thought of it before.

03:59.906 --> 04:01.407
But they hadn't.

04:01.491 --> 04:04.410
He just understood the game better
than anybody else.

04:06.120 --> 04:08.957
Which made his organization better.

04:10.458 --> 04:12.085
Ah!

04:13.336 --> 04:14.337
Ah!

04:14.420 --> 04:15.421
[laughs]

04:15.505 --> 04:16.923
It made them fucking winners.

04:26.766 --> 04:29.435
By uniting the plazas
into a single organization,

04:29.811 --> 04:32.772
Félix created Mexico's first narco union.

04:37.819 --> 04:39.487
[siren blares]

04:43.074 --> 04:45.159
[bleating]

04:52.250 --> 04:53.418
-[in Spanish] It's 200?
-Yes.

04:55.545 --> 04:58.464
[narrator] By partnering
with the traffickers' natural enemy,

04:58.548 --> 05:01.301
he made his system virtually unstoppable.

05:02.010 --> 05:04.137
-[in Spanish] You're good to go.
-[driver] Thank you.

05:06.431 --> 05:08.182
[horns honking]

05:08.266 --> 05:09.767
[cameras clicking]

05:09.851 --> 05:12.478
[narrator in English] The cops
even gave themselves fucking medals

05:12.562 --> 05:14.063
for taking out the competition.

05:14.147 --> 05:15.815
[cheering and applause]

05:22.739 --> 05:24.991
And the cash was rolling in.

05:31.080 --> 05:34.375
So much money that Félix
actually opened accounts in the States

05:34.459 --> 05:37.462
to manage cash flow
and protect his profits.

05:38.838 --> 05:41.007
We're talking over $30 million a week

05:41.090 --> 05:43.885
in the hands
of a bunch of Sinaloan cowboys.

05:43.968 --> 05:44.927
[in Spanish] Look, Rafa.

05:45.470 --> 05:47.180
You gotta watch this.

05:47.930 --> 05:48.848
Al Pacino.

05:48.931 --> 05:49.807
Scarface.

05:49.891 --> 05:50.975
No, bro.

05:51.726 --> 05:54.062
I'll tell you what we need to do:

05:54.312 --> 05:58.733
build a ramp and see if we can
get this motherfucker over the pool.

05:58.816 --> 05:59.650
Let's go!

05:59.734 --> 06:01.569
[men chattering]

06:01.652 --> 06:04.989
[narrator in English] What were good guys
doing while all of this was going down?

06:05.698 --> 06:08.117
Waiting
for the wheels of bureaucracy to turn.

06:08.868 --> 06:12.163
Specifically, a request
for Mexican surveillance flights

06:12.246 --> 06:13.873
over the northern desert.

06:14.540 --> 06:16.292
But after months of waiting,

06:16.376 --> 06:20.797
proof that something big was happening
outside of Jalisco had finally arrived.

06:22.965 --> 06:25.885
Or at least, that was the fucking plan.

06:32.225 --> 06:33.476
[in English] The fuck is this?

06:45.738 --> 06:47.949
[sighs]

06:52.703 --> 06:54.539
-That's it.
-[Kiki] That's it?

06:54.997 --> 06:56.749
We waited three months for this?

06:57.375 --> 07:00.420
This is bullshit.
You guys know that, right?

07:00.503 --> 07:02.880
Maybe those trucks weren't heading
to a marijuana grow.

07:02.964 --> 07:04.799
[Sears] You know nothing
grows in the desert?

07:04.882 --> 07:06.259
Well, it does if you irrigate it.

07:06.342 --> 07:07.885
What'd you think all the pipes were for?

07:07.969 --> 07:10.096
We hear anything about this
from any of our CIs?

07:10.179 --> 07:11.097
-No.
-Nada.

07:11.180 --> 07:14.809
All right, so the problem is we have
a U.S.-funded aerial eradication program

07:14.892 --> 07:17.311
that says nothing's there. For miles.

07:17.395 --> 07:19.772
If they didn't find anything,
they didn't want to.

07:19.856 --> 07:22.817
The eradication program
is either broken or bought and paid for

07:22.900 --> 07:25.778
-by whoever's running this fucking thing.
-[Sears] No one is running this.

07:25.862 --> 07:27.447
It's the wild fucking west.

07:27.530 --> 07:29.490
You read the same cables that I do.

07:29.574 --> 07:31.409
When Pedro Avilés
and the Naranjo brothers died,

07:31.492 --> 07:34.787
what happened to the price of weed?
It stabilized from L.A. to Houston.

07:34.871 --> 07:37.874
Because it's coming from the same
organization, the same fucking source.

07:37.957 --> 07:39.876
[sighs]
Your mysterious super-field.

07:39.959 --> 07:44.297
Mexicans don't work like that, Kiki, okay?
Organized, structured. They just...

07:44.964 --> 07:46.215
Look, no offense.

07:46.299 --> 07:49.469
Hey. You're making some big leaps, okay?

07:49.552 --> 07:51.554
Price of weed holding steady
for a couple of months?

07:51.637 --> 07:54.765
Yeah, that could mean something,
but it also could just be a coincidence.

07:55.766 --> 07:59.437
If you want, I can try
and request another recon flight.

07:59.520 --> 08:01.314
That going to change anything?

08:02.565 --> 08:05.193
We work with the system we got.

08:05.401 --> 08:07.528
Well, the joke's on us,
because the system's busted.

08:09.155 --> 08:10.865
I mean, are you guys okay with that?

08:10.948 --> 08:14.035
Chasing some Mickey Mouse bust
while some asshole's changing the game

08:14.118 --> 08:16.537
-right under our fucking noses?
-[Knapp] Look, man, hey,

08:16.621 --> 08:20.166
if there's a new doper in town, sooner
or later, someone's gonna take him out.

08:20.249 --> 08:22.960
-That's the way it works down here.
-Nothing down here works.

08:23.044 --> 08:24.045
Enlighten us.

08:24.128 --> 08:28.716
Do you have a plan for reversing decades
of institutional corruption or is this it?

08:28.799 --> 08:32.386
Turns out all we needed to fix Mexico
was a well-timed temper tantrum.

08:32.470 --> 08:35.306
Is it that you don't give a shit,
or it's been so long

08:35.389 --> 08:37.600
you forgot what doing your job
actually looks like?

08:38.226 --> 08:40.561
-You want to run that by me outside?
-I'd love to, pal.

08:41.312 --> 08:43.689
-All right. Hey! Enough of this shit!
-Fuck you!

08:43.773 --> 08:46.776
Hey, it's five o'clock. Shouldn't you be
at the Camelot drinking beers by now?

08:46.859 --> 08:49.445
Enough! Calm down! You go for a walk.

08:50.404 --> 08:51.364
Cool off.

08:54.200 --> 08:56.827
Somebody should call D.C.
and tell them we surrendered Guadalajara.

08:57.912 --> 08:58.996
[door slams]

08:59.080 --> 09:00.540
[sighs]

09:03.376 --> 09:06.337
[in Spanish]
We have 72 rooms and 6 suites.

09:07.004 --> 09:08.923
I can't believe this is all yours.

09:09.757 --> 09:12.009
-[Félix] It's an investment, Rodolfo.
-An investment?

09:12.301 --> 09:16.222
The IBM stock I got from my father
was an investment. [chuckles]

09:16.305 --> 09:18.849
Look, we'll put two bars
for your reception over there

09:18.933 --> 09:21.310
so the guests can come out
and drink in the evening.

09:21.394 --> 09:22.520
Mm.

09:23.271 --> 09:24.897
Gabriela's going to love it.

09:26.148 --> 09:29.068
I can't thank you enough, Miguel.

09:29.151 --> 09:32.697
You don't have to thank me.
Thank me for what, man?

09:33.155 --> 09:36.325
I used to watch you run around
in your underwear, terrorizing nannies.

09:38.828 --> 09:40.913
Governor Celis. Welcome.

09:40.997 --> 09:42.498
[chattering]

09:42.582 --> 09:44.333
-How are you?
-Can't complain.

09:44.417 --> 09:45.501
Three governors.

09:45.585 --> 09:48.212
-Governor Ocaña García.
-Yes, I know who you are.

09:48.296 --> 09:50.131
-Governor Álvarez.
-Nice to meet you.

09:50.214 --> 09:52.800
-Governor Del Castillo Franco.
-Delighted.

09:52.883 --> 09:57.430
Allow me to introduce our host,
Miguel Ángel Félix Gallardo.

09:57.680 --> 10:01.851
A hundred years ago, Miguel Ángel
worked as a bodyguard for my family

10:01.934 --> 10:04.145
back when he was in the state police.

10:04.812 --> 10:07.356
Your aunt's here. Go say hello.

10:08.649 --> 10:09.734
Go.

10:10.151 --> 10:11.110
Excuse me.

10:11.360 --> 10:13.654
I'll let you finish, but maybe after,

10:13.738 --> 10:16.282
I can show you the ballroom
we're using for the reception.

10:16.365 --> 10:19.201
-I'd like your approval.
-We'll join you shortly.

10:19.285 --> 10:21.579
I'll leave you to it then.
Make yourselves at home.

10:21.662 --> 10:23.789
-Excuse me.
-Congratulations.

10:26.208 --> 10:29.253
[Maria] You know you weren't
this nervous before we got married.

10:29.337 --> 10:30.796
[chuckles]

10:30.880 --> 10:35.217
And our entire wedding cost less
than the damn cake you bought.

10:35.718 --> 10:38.471
We didn't have half the governors
of Mexico on our guest list.

10:39.138 --> 10:41.057
Your dad paid for our wedding.
I was quite broke.

10:41.140 --> 10:42.266
That I remember.

10:43.893 --> 10:45.061
Miguel?

10:46.103 --> 10:49.398
You think if you impress these people,
they're going to accept you?

10:49.482 --> 10:51.984
I just want the wedding to be perfect.

10:52.568 --> 10:54.320
You certainly want to impress Celis.

10:54.403 --> 10:55.821
And what if I do?

10:55.905 --> 10:58.491
Hmm? So?

10:58.574 --> 11:00.785
That man was the closest thing
I had to a father.

11:00.910 --> 11:02.578
Seriously. Am I wrong?

11:03.079 --> 11:04.538
I owe him.

11:05.164 --> 11:06.374
[intercom beeping]

11:07.166 --> 11:08.250
What's up?

11:08.417 --> 11:10.628
[woman]
Mr. Félix, you have a call.

11:12.171 --> 11:13.464
[Félix]
I have to take this call.

11:15.383 --> 11:18.052
I'll be home soon. Have to get up early.

11:18.135 --> 11:21.722
For what? To inspect the imported napkins?

11:21.806 --> 11:22.973
Oh, come on.

11:25.935 --> 11:26.811
What's up?

11:26.894 --> 11:29.188
[Don Neto]
Sorry to interrupt the ball, Cinderella.

11:30.189 --> 11:32.024
We've got a problem.

11:32.900 --> 11:35.152
[narrator in English]
There's one problem with success.

11:35.736 --> 11:37.321
Not everyone can handle it.

11:38.406 --> 11:43.202
When things go well, people start thinking
it's because they're so fucking smart.

11:46.956 --> 11:50.626
But guess what happens when you
put wolves and bears on the same team?

11:50.710 --> 11:53.379
-[in Spanish] What the fuck is this?
-Those are the leftovers.

11:53.462 --> 11:54.672
Leftovers?

11:54.755 --> 11:56.257
Fucking Sinaloans.

11:57.925 --> 12:00.761
-Right.
-[narrator in English] Someone gets eaten.

12:02.555 --> 12:04.557
[overlapping chatter]

12:09.603 --> 12:11.313
[vehicle approaching]

12:14.734 --> 12:16.944
-[in Spanish] The hell do you want?
-[gunshots]

12:17.027 --> 12:18.571
Victor!

12:18.654 --> 12:19.613
[gunshots]

12:20.614 --> 12:21.699
[screaming]

12:29.874 --> 12:31.959
[choking]

12:35.755 --> 12:37.089
What the fuck?

12:37.631 --> 12:38.841
The leftovers.

12:40.092 --> 12:41.969
[narrator in English]
But it doesn't end there.

12:42.052 --> 12:45.723
Because in the Mexican narcotics game,
everyone's related.

12:45.806 --> 12:48.559
[Benjamín in Spanish] The cops
just took out Victor Molina and his crew.

12:49.059 --> 12:51.896
They killed cousin Beto. He's dead, man.

12:57.985 --> 12:59.445
[in Spanish] Fucking cops.

13:00.070 --> 13:04.325
Molina family's been moving weed
since Nava's father was in diapers.

13:04.408 --> 13:07.453
Had their thumbs on the scale
for about that long, too.

13:07.661 --> 13:08.996
But still...

13:09.705 --> 13:12.374
the Arellano Félix brothers
want blood for their cousin.

13:12.458 --> 13:13.417
True.

13:13.501 --> 13:15.127
Kid was well-liked.

13:15.211 --> 13:16.504
Enough.

13:17.421 --> 13:19.298
We have to get the cops back in line.

13:19.381 --> 13:20.883
Police reform?

13:21.884 --> 13:23.010
Are you drunk?

13:23.093 --> 13:25.221
Seems like you don't give a shit, Neto.

13:26.555 --> 13:29.183
I'm talking to you! Then give me an idea.

13:29.266 --> 13:33.521
The number two guy doesn't solve problems.
He just points them out.

13:33.604 --> 13:34.897
[chuckles]

13:35.564 --> 13:36.690
What do you think of her?

13:38.317 --> 13:39.193
As an actress?

13:40.444 --> 13:42.112
No. As a date.

13:42.571 --> 13:45.241
-Pretty hot, no?
-Yes, she's hot.

13:45.324 --> 13:48.202
Miguel is throwing the party of the year.

13:48.285 --> 13:50.871
I want to make the right impression
on his fancy new friends.

13:50.955 --> 13:53.582
You're a smart guy, skinny.

13:54.625 --> 13:56.502
You'll figure it out.
Just don't take too long.

13:56.585 --> 13:59.255
Our guys are already asking questions.

13:59.338 --> 14:02.132
Any of these crazy motherfuckers
start a war with the DFS...

14:03.551 --> 14:06.804
-this thing is over and done with.
-I'll talk to Nava.

14:19.650 --> 14:21.277
[microwave beeps]

14:25.531 --> 14:28.158
-[Mika in English] Kiki, is that you?
-No.

14:30.119 --> 14:31.161
You ready?

14:31.579 --> 14:32.705
Ready for what?

14:32.788 --> 14:34.415
-The barbecue.
-What barbecue?

14:34.498 --> 14:35.958
You were there when Rita called.

14:36.667 --> 14:38.085
Who the fuck is Rita?

14:38.168 --> 14:41.171
Rita Knapp. Roger's wife.

14:41.255 --> 14:44.758
-Roger Knapp's barbecue's tonight?
-Yes. Another case cracked.

14:44.842 --> 14:46.802
-Come on, get ready.
-No.

14:46.886 --> 14:49.763
-What do you mean, no?
-I mean I'm not gonna go.

14:52.516 --> 14:53.517
[scoffs]

14:53.601 --> 14:56.103
[pop music playing]

14:56.937 --> 14:58.647
[chatter in background]

15:03.193 --> 15:05.321
[distant laughs]

15:05.988 --> 15:10.534
Oh, you all see that cable
that came in from the Mazatlán office?

15:10.618 --> 15:15.039
You want us to keep tabs on some guy
coming in from, uh... Sinaloa?

15:15.122 --> 15:16.123
What's his name?

15:18.208 --> 15:20.711
Coch... Cochiloco?

15:20.794 --> 15:22.421
Cochi-something.

15:22.880 --> 15:24.131
I don't know. We got it.

15:25.424 --> 15:27.551
I mean, I like that he said,
"Little chance."

15:28.260 --> 15:29.595
Roger loved that.

15:29.678 --> 15:31.472
[laughing]

15:31.555 --> 15:32.389
[Ana]
Of course!

15:39.563 --> 15:41.231
[tuning guitar]

15:44.151 --> 15:47.071
So, you guys like those burgers?

15:47.488 --> 15:49.156
-Of course.
-[Rita] Yeah, mine was great.

15:49.531 --> 15:51.492
-Honey, they were really good.
-I told you, baby.

15:51.575 --> 15:52.660
[laughs]

15:59.750 --> 16:01.377
Have you guys seen Kiki's ID yet?

16:03.170 --> 16:04.296
-[Rita] No. No.
-[Jaime] Mmm.

16:04.588 --> 16:05.673
Come on, show them.

16:07.800 --> 16:08.717
Babe, it's funny.

16:19.687 --> 16:21.313
[Kiki clears throat]

16:23.065 --> 16:25.567
-Is that a black eye?
-[Knapp] Let me see that, babe.

16:25.651 --> 16:28.445
[Mika] The week Kiki got accepted
into the DEA, we're at this wedding.

16:28.529 --> 16:32.574
Actually, we crashed it, but Calexico's
so small, everybody knows each other.

16:33.367 --> 16:36.203
So we have a few drinks,
everything's fine.

16:36.829 --> 16:40.708
Then this kid comes to the table to tell
his mom he can't go to the bathroom

16:40.791 --> 16:42.501
because there was
a guy in there smoking pot.

16:42.584 --> 16:44.670
[Rita]
Uh-oh. Busted.

16:44.753 --> 16:47.715
[Mika] Right. So brand-new federal agent
here is like, "I got this."

16:47.798 --> 16:49.508
-Heads off to the bathroom.
-[laughter]

16:49.591 --> 16:53.303
-So what happened?
-Well, it wasn't one guy, it was four.

16:53.387 --> 16:55.264
-[Knapp] Oh, I like those odds.
-[laughs]

16:55.347 --> 16:57.182
[Mika] So he says to them,

16:57.266 --> 17:01.020
"We can do this the easy way
or we can do it the hard way."

17:01.979 --> 17:04.481
Turns out the easy way
was to beat the shit out of me.

17:04.565 --> 17:06.400
All this for a joint, right?

17:07.192 --> 17:11.655
[chuckles] So I ask him,
"Was it worth it? Are you happy now?"

17:12.072 --> 17:15.784
And I said, "I had them on possession,
but now I have them on assault,

17:15.868 --> 17:17.911
so damn right it was worth it."

17:17.995 --> 17:19.413
[Sears]
Hell, yeah.

17:19.496 --> 17:21.707
[Knapp] You know what?
That story'll make me write a song.

17:22.082 --> 17:23.542
Called "Damn Right It Was Worth It."

17:23.625 --> 17:25.169
[laughter]

17:28.338 --> 17:30.049
[Kiki] Why did you tell them that story?

17:30.132 --> 17:32.634
Because it's funny. It's who you are.

17:32.718 --> 17:35.888
-Yeah, I don't need them to like me.
-Yeah, but I do.

17:36.805 --> 17:38.474
I'm down here alone, Kiki.

17:38.557 --> 17:41.643
I need to talk to other adults sometimes
to actually make friends.

17:41.727 --> 17:45.064
And it helps if the other Americans
don't all think my husband's an asshole.

17:45.147 --> 17:46.440
I'm not an asshole.

17:46.523 --> 17:47.858
Not all the time.

17:52.696 --> 17:54.073
I don't care what they think.

18:00.996 --> 18:02.164
[siren blares]

18:29.608 --> 18:31.110
[in Spanish]
Let's go. Get out.

18:33.320 --> 18:34.446
[turns off engine]

18:37.866 --> 18:39.535
[chatter over radio]

18:58.262 --> 19:00.848
[Nava]
Come in, man.

19:06.019 --> 19:07.312
Have something for you.

19:08.313 --> 19:09.815
You look good.

19:10.858 --> 19:16.738
Miguel Ángel. Agent number 1178.

19:17.239 --> 19:19.908
This is the key that opens all the doors.

19:21.243 --> 19:24.746
-I hear you want to talk.
-[Félix] Yeah.

19:25.998 --> 19:28.208
This business with Victor Molina--

19:28.292 --> 19:31.587
He crossed the line.
He was stealing from us.

19:35.090 --> 19:37.259
You seem to have forgotten one thing.

19:37.926 --> 19:41.722
Almost all of us are family
in this organization.

19:42.514 --> 19:46.977
The guy you killed
is the cousin of another guy.

19:47.394 --> 19:49.980
